                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p35m62q08/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "\n                              <p>nations among whom they have been dispersed for the holiest<lb/>\n                                        and mightiest of purposes, consent to join in it, and I\n                                        feel<lb/> persuaded that at no remote period after the\n                                        formation of<lb/> such an association it will reckon among\n                                        its members<lb/> almost every Israelite in these states.\n                                        should your proposal<lb/> in the occident for ministers of\n                                        the different synagogues<lb/> to meet in the ensuing spring\n                                        be embraced by them generally<lb/> it may lead to important\n                                        results. You are but an indiffer<lb/>-ent correspondent yet\n                                        I trust a reply to this will not be <sic>witheld</sic><lb/>\n                                        by you, and that I may anticipate your having success\n                                        fully<lb/> used your kind endeavours to circulate the\n                                        Retrospect—<lb/> as it will have the double purpose of\n                                        serving me and<lb/> promoting the common cause.—Has\n                                                  <persName>Mr. Abm Hart</persName> got<lb/> a copy\n                                        from you? Had my time permitted of it I would<lb/> when at\n                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> have gone over\n                                        with you the points<lb/> that work treats. You have it in\n                                        your power to do much<lb/> towards calling attention to\n                                        publications of this description<lb/> and I feel assured\n                                        that whatever you can do towards aiding<lb/> such efforts\n                                        will not be <sic>witheld</sic>, especially as you are<lb/>\n                                        well aware of the uphill work those have to encounter\n                                        who<lb/> through the press attempt to rouse our people to\n                                        action</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">As you have many opportunities of seeing\n                                                  <persName>Miss Gratz</persName><lb/> will you do\n                                        me the favor to mention me respectfully to her<lb/> that\n                                        when I left for her the letter entrusted to me by\n                                                  <persName>Mrs.<lb/> Etting</persName> I fully\n                                        expected to have had the pleasure of waiting<lb/> upon her\n                                        on my return to <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> from\n                                                  <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> &amp; regret\n                                        exceedingly being deprived of doing so from the<lb/>\n                                        necessity I was under of returning home by way of\n                                                  <placeName>Albany</placeName></p>\n                              "
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p35m62q08/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
